{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.36,0.14,0.27,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10444"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63184"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5178"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24389"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA General Practitioner considers prescribing a medication that works by increasing supraspinal availability of noradrenaline, has peripheral anti-inflammatory effects, and increases activation of endogenous opioid systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drug classes is being considered for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antipyretic analgesics","Antidepressants","Anticonvulsants","Cannabinoids","Opioids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe drug class being considered is \u003Cstrong\u003Eantidepressants\u003C/strong\u003E. Certain antidepressants, particularly those that inhibit the reuptake of noradrenaline and serotonin, can have analgesic effects. These effects are due to increased supraspinal availability of noradrenaline, peripheral anti-inflammatory effects, and enhanced activation of endogenous opioid systems. This makes them useful in managing chronic pain conditions, especially when there is a coexisting mood disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntipyretic analgesics\u003C/strong\u003E, such as paracetamol, primarily work by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis in the central nervous system and do not have the described mechanisms of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticonvulsants\u003C/strong\u003E are often used for neuropathic pain and work by stabilising neuronal membranes and inhibiting excitatory neurotransmitter release, but they do not primarily increase noradrenaline availability or activate opioid systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECannabinoids\u003C/strong\u003E have analgesic properties through different mechanisms, including modulation of cannabinoid receptors, but they do not primarily increase noradrenaline availability or have significant peripheral anti-inflammatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioids\u003C/strong\u003E provide analgesia by binding to opioid receptors in the central nervous system, but they do not increase supraspinal availability of noradrenaline or have peripheral anti-inflammatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Antidepressants can increase supraspinal availability of noradrenaline, have peripheral anti-inflammatory effects, and enhance activation of endogenous opioid systems.","These mechanisms contribute to the analgesic effects of certain antidepressants, making them useful in managing chronic pain conditions."],"references":["Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560692/","Stahl SM. Basic psychopharmacology of antidepressants, part 1: Antidepressants have seven distinct mechanisms of action. J Clin Psychiatry. 1998;59 Suppl 4:5-14. PMID: 9554316.","Machado-Vieira R, Salvadore G, Luckenbaugh DA, Manji HK, Zarate CA Jr. Rapid onset of antidepressant action: a new paradigm in the research and treatment of major depressive disorder. J Clin Psychiatry. 2008 Jun;69(6):946-58. doi: 10.4088/jcp.v69n0610. PMID: 18435563; PMCID: PMC2699451.","Taylor C, Fricker AD, Devi LA, Gomes I. Mechanisms of action of antidepressants: from neurotransmitter systems to signaling pathways. Cell Signal. 2005 May;17(5):549-57. doi: 10.1016/j.cellsig.2004.12.007. PMID: 15683730; PMCID: PMC3581018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63184"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63184"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:30:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:05:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10444"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77671"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attribu